    \begin{block}{Aims}
    \begin{itemize}
    \item{Ensure that researchers leave the institute with competency in numerical and computational analysis. We focus on core skills in {\color{crukpink}{statistics}}, {\color{crukblue}{experimental design}}, {\color{crukpink}{R}}, {\color{crukblue}{Reproducible Research}}  and {\color{crukpink}{unix}}.}
    \item{Increase researcher independence by promoting interfaces such as IGV, Galaxy and UCSC for routine Bioinformatics analysis and data exploration}
    \item{Monitor and advertise Bioinformatics training opportunities that arise in the University}
    \end{itemize}
    \end{block}
    \begin{block}{Experimental Design and Statistics}



  
        {\color{crukpink}{\textit{"To consult the statistician after an experiment is finished is often merely to ask him to conduct a post mortem examination. He can perhaps say what the experiment died of." - R.A. Fisher}}}
        
This quote by Fisher sums up why experimental design is a crucial part of the experimental process. For this reason, our training course on Experimental Design is \textbf{compulsory} for all new PhD students. The course is also run regularly for other researchers at C.I.\\


Statistics teaching is done using the R Commander GUI; a user-friendly way of doing statistical analysis in R (\cite{Rcmdr}). Therefore the focus of this training is on the statistical concepts, rather than wrestling with the R language. In this course we introduce the basics of statistics and hypothesis testing. 
Material from our experimental design and statistics courses are available on {\color{crukblue}{Sharepoint}}. Individual consultations with the Statistics team can be arranged by emailing; {\color{crukpink}{{\tt cristatsclinic@cruk.cam.ac.uk}}}\vspace{1cm}


 
    \end{block}
